I"ê<h2 id="ingredients">Ingredients</h2>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Vidalia Onyo</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Sugar</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Balsamic Vinegar</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Unsalted Butter</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Water</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Salt</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Pepper</p>
  </li>
</ol>

<h2 id="steps">Steps</h2>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Take Onyo</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Slice Onyo into very long and slim strips</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Put 1 Tbsp. of Butter into pan</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Turn heat on to Medium-High</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Put Onyo in the pan as soon as the butter melts</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Season with Salt and Pepper</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Wait until it starts sizzling quite heavily</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Pour a bit of water to cover the bottom of the pan</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Close the lid and let the Onyo steam</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>After the water evaporates, Mix/toss the Onyo in the pan so that it does not burn and add more water</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Repeat process until onyo becomes soft and start developping color.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Depending on the Quality and age of the balsamic vinegar, more or less sugar may be required
as younger balsamic vinegars tend to be more acidic.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Pour the sugar and balsamic vinegar into the Onyo. The quantity should depend on your prefered taste. It should taste neither too sweet, neither too sour.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Mix up the vinegar and sugar into the Onyo and reduce until the Onyo absorbs all the vinegar.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Plate up and serve. Eat as condiment or (hopefully not) as meal.</p>
  </li>
</ol>

:ET